    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Diplomatic Erosion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Vinca LaFleur letter on Sept 1 article scores Republican-led Congress for playing partisan politics with Peter Burleigh's ambassadorial appointment</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Stymied by Senate, Would-Be Envoy Quits'' (news item, Sept. 1):</p>
        <p>Peter Burleigh's departure represents not just the loss of a talented, respected public servant but also the dangerous erosion of America's diplomatic resources at the hands of a shortsighted Congress.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Stymied by Senate, Would-Be Envoy Quits'' (news item, Sept. 1):</p>
        <p>Peter Burleigh's departure represents not just the loss of a talented, respected public servant but also the dangerous erosion of America's diplomatic resources at the hands of a shortsighted Congress.</p>
        <p>Whether dragging its feet on paying our dues to multilateral institutions like the United Nations, paring back the State Department's already modest budget, or playing partisan politics with ambassadorial appointments, the Republican-led Congress has undervalued, underfinanced and undermined crucial tools of American leadership abroad.</p>
        <p>Maintaining our global pre-eminence demands much more than a powerful military. And the stronger our diplomacy, the better the chance that we won't have to put our servicemen and women in harm's way.</p>
        <p>VINCA LAFLEUR  Washington, Sept. 1, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer was a special assistant to the president, 1995-98.</p>
      </block>
